        First Bancorp completes Carolina Bank purchase
    


By Richard Craver
Winston-Salem Journal








Richard Craver



















Mar 7, 2017
 (…)





































































































First Bancorp has completed a two-prong expansion into the Triad by completing its $93 million deal for Carolina Bank Holdings Inc. on Friday.First Bancorp, based in Southern Pines, has increased its Winston-Salem and Triad presence significantly in the past year.It is likely to enter the Top 10 for North Carolina deposits with the acquisition of the Greensboro bank.First Bancorp has 19 branches in the Triad and 94 in North Carolina. It increases its total assets to $4.3 billion and deposits to $3.6 billion.“We’re an 80-year-old bank that’s the fifth largest based in North Carolina,” Richard Moore, First Bancorp’s chief executive and former state treasurer, said in July.“We’ve had a small presence in the southern Triad but knew our future would be tied to having a bigger presence in the parts of the state growing the fastest.“Our goal the past three years is to make that happen, and Winston-Salem will play a key role as part of the most natural expansion we can make right now, “ Moore said.Following the closing date, Carolina shareholders will be mailed an election form with instructions and a deadline for electing how they wish to be compensated in terms of cash and stock. The accepted offer was worth $19.26 a share, based on 75 percent stock and 25 percent cash.The bank said it expects to convert the Carolina branches in August.Carolina Bank, the bank subsidiary of Carolina Bank Holdings, will continue to operate as Carolina Bank until it is merged into First Bank.First Bancorp entered the Winston-Salem market in July when it completed the acquisition of four branches of First Community Bancshares Inc.,Upon completion of the purchase, Forsyth County would be First Bancorp’s largest branch market at eight when using that measuring stick.However, it is likely to close one branch between a former First Community branch and a Carolina Bank branch that are less than a mile apart off Stratford Road and Knollwood Street.Chris Marinac, managing principal with FIG Partners of Atlanta, said he viewed First Bancorp’s growth initiative and its Small Business Administration activities as positive for generating additional fee income, positive operating leverage and earnings per share.
“First Bancorp is executing on its new goal of entering higher growth markets and enhance longer-term return on assets,” Marinac said.Moore said First Bancorp has two main advantages over those super-community bank competitors, two of which — BNC Bancorp and Yadkin Financial Corp. — are in the process of being bought by regional banks.The first, Moore said, is its focus on traditional community bank lending to individuals, and small- to medium-sized businesses in the $1 million to $25 million sweet spot.The second is that unlike BNC, Capital and Yadkin, First Bancorp has no private-equity groups with a large ownership stake. The other banks sold such stakes as part of surviving the financial crisis of 2008-11 and rashes of defaulting residential mortgages and commercial real-estate loans.“We understand the Triad economy, the changes it’s going through,” Moore said.“We are absolutely confident there is a place for a bank like ours with the economies of scale we have because, traditionally, there always has been.”






rcraver@wsjournal.com (336) 727-7376 @rcraverWSJ














































